<paragraph blockId="66.[151,609,835,862]" box="[151,609,835,862]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,609,835,862]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,609,835,862]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Key to the species groups of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker. A" authorityYear="1857" box="[505,609,836,862]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[505,609,836,862]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="key">
<key pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
1. Forewings with prominent dark marks along the apical crossveins between Cu and Ms2 usually arranged in 2 rows of 4 spots each (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[326,419,935,956]" captionStart="FIGURE 230" captionStartId="260.[151,244,1534,1555]" captionTargetBox="[209,1399,1018,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-49@260.[178,1410,996,1513]" captionTargetPageId="260" captionText="FIGURE 230. Rhotana panthera, a–o holotype ♂; s paratype ♂, apical part of aedeagus in dorsal view." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 230f</figureCitation>
). The marks may be close together, only separated by red veins (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1095,1184,935,956]" captionStart="FIGURE 231" captionStartId="261.[151,244,979,1000]" captionTargetBox="[188,1410,198,949]" captionTargetId="figure-35@261.[175,1412,191,957]" captionTargetPageId="261" captionText="FIGURE 231. Rhotana papuensis, holotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 231f</figureCitation>
or 237f). If only one row then at least 3 spots present and area near the crossveins and the marks bright red (
<figureCitation box="[1016,1106,965,986]" captionStart="FIGURE 222" captionStartId="256.[151,244,1704,1725]" captionTargetBox="[185,1400,1208,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-52@256.[175,1412,1197,1683]" captionTargetPageId="256" captionText="FIGURE 222. Rhotana deminuta, holotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 222f</figureCitation>
)...... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zelazny" authorityYear="1981" baseAuthorityName="Bierman" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1177,1314,965,986]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavo">
<emphasis box="[1177,1314,965,986]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana pavo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, p. 84
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" box="[151,1436,994,1015]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,994,1015]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">- Forewings not coloured in this way....................................................................... 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
2. Forewings colourless, but with some dark spots, the most prominent spots near the apex of Cu just distad of the apex of the clavus and at the base of the 1st subcostal sector (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[714,803,1053,1074]" captionStart="FIGURE 216" captionStartId="255.[151,244,574,595]" captionTargetBox="[181,1401,188,553]" captionTargetId="figure-49@255.[177,1409,165,564]" captionTargetPageId="255" captionText="FIGURE 216. Rhotana pacata, holotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 216f</figureCitation>
)............................ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zelazny" authorityYear="1981" box="[1163,1314,1053,1074]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis box="[1163,1314,1053,1074]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana ornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, p. 82
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" box="[151,1436,1082,1103]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1082,1103]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">- Forewings not coloured this way, if they are colourless then without these spots.................................... 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" box="[151,1436,1111,1132]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1111,1132]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
3. Hindwings with dark marks near hindmargin between apices of Cu and R (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[984,1085,1111,1132]" captionStart="FIGURE 207" captionStartId="251.[151,244,1937,1958]" captionTargetBox="[197,1390,1236,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-37@251.[182,1405,1230,1916]" captionTargetPageId="251" captionText="FIGURE 207. Rhotana maculata. f–p holotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Figs. 
<quantity box="[1037,1085,1111,1132]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.07" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="g" value="207.0">207g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
or 
<quantity box="[1117,1166,1111,1132]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.97" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="g" value="197.0">197g</quantity>
).................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Hindwings may be colourless or with some infuscations, but without dark marks (a small elongated mark may be present around apex of Ms1, see 
<figureCitation box="[465,559,1170,1191]" captionStart="FIGURE 240" captionStartId="265.[151,244,873,894]" captionTargetBox="[182,1394,185,858]" captionTargetId="figure-41@265.[177,1411,179,870]" captionTargetPageId="265" captionText="FIGURE 240. Rhotana albata, lectotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[510,559,1170,1191]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.4" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="g" value="240.0">240g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
)....................................................................... 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
4. Hindwing marks small and located around the M-Ms1 and/or M-Ms2 forks, forewings with anterior apical crossveins lined with dark stripes (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[439,536,1229,1250]" captionStart="FIGURE 196" captionStartId="246.[151,244,1301,1322]" captionTargetBox="[207,1367,561,1277]" captionTargetId="figure-47@246.[200,1381,548,1288]" captionTargetPageId="246" captionText="FIGURE 196. Rhotana formosana, lectotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Figs. 196f</figureCitation>
or 197f)......................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Matsumura" authorityYear="1914" box="[1124,1313,1229,1250]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosana">
<emphasis box="[1124,1313,1229,1250]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana formosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, p. 67
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Hindwing marks larger (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[501,595,1258,1279]" captionStart="FIGURE 206" captionStartId="251.[151,244,1161,1182]" captionTargetBox="[195,1407,205,1135]" captionTargetId="figure-33@251.[176,1411,191,1139]" captionTargetPageId="251" captionText="FIGURE 206. Rhotana latipennis, lectotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[546,595,1258,1279]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.06" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="g" value="206.0">206g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
) and anterior apical crossveins of forewings not lined with dark stripes......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1857" box="[1129,1314,1288,1309]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latipennis">
<emphasis box="[1129,1314,1288,1309]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana latipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, p. 71
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
5. Forewings very broad, only 1.7 times longer than wide or less (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[889,983,1317,1338]" captionStart="FIGURE 212" captionStartId="253.[151,244,1718,1739]" captionTargetBox="[190,1396,977,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-36@253.[177,1410,959,1698]" captionTargetPageId="253" captionText="FIGURE 212. Rhotana melichari, holotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 212f</figureCitation>
); facial carinae separated throughout (e.g. 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 212" captionStartId="253.[151,244,1718,1739]" captionTargetBox="[190,1396,977,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-36@253.[177,1410,959,1698]" captionTargetPageId="253" captionText="FIGURE 212. Rhotana melichari, holotype ♂." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 212c</figureCitation>
)....................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zelazny &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2011" box="[1135,1314,1346,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melichari">
<emphasis box="[1135,1314,1346,1367]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana melichari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, p. 79
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" box="[151,1436,1375,1396]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1375,1396]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">- Forewings not that broad or if very broad facial carinae contiguous at their base.................................... 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
6. Forewings with dark spots on median sectors near their apices (at least on Ms3 and Ms4), facial carinae separated throughout (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[273,361,1434,1455]" captionStart="FIGURE 238" captionStartId="264.[151,244,764,785]" captionTargetBox="[199,1405,207,732]" captionTargetId="figure-42@264.[177,1411,191,743]" captionTargetPageId="264" captionText="FIGURE 238. Rhotana quadrimaculata, c, f lectotype (sex unknown); remainder, specimen from Hutchinson creek, N. Queensland." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 238f</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[408,499,1434,1455]" captionStart="FIGURE 238" captionStartId="264.[151,244,764,785]" captionTargetBox="[199,1405,207,732]" captionTargetId="figure-42@264.[177,1411,191,743]" captionTargetPageId="264" captionText="FIGURE 238. Rhotana quadrimaculata, c, f lectotype (sex unknown); remainder, specimen from Hutchinson creek, N. Queensland." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 238c</figureCitation>
)............................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1907" box="[1069,1313,1434,1455]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrimaculata">
<emphasis box="[1069,1313,1434,1455]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana quadrimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, p. 95
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,906,1485]" box="[151,1436,1463,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1463,1485]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Forewings without these spots and facial carinae usually contiguous at their base......... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker. A" authorityYear="1857" box="[1111,1192,1464,1485]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1111,1192,1464,1485]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Rhotana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ungrouped species, p. 97
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
</subSubSection>
